    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-02T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-02T02:00:00-05:00" n="827"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d827">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11408: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-02T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 2, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 2—8:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>588. Department’s 326, December 1, 8 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Department presumably will have noted our 582, November 30, 7 p.m.,
                        (to which reference was made in Shanghai’s 1050, December 1, 11 a.m.<note
                            n="70" xml:id="d827fn70">Telegram No. 1050, not printed.</note>) in
                        which case we reported having taken action in anticipation of the
                        Department’s instructions.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Today we informed the Foreign Office of the statement made by the Japanese
                        Assistant Military Attaché at British military headquarters, as reported in
                        Shanghai’s 1057,<note n="71" xml:id="d827fn71">December 1, 7 p.m. <ref
                                target="#pg_742">p. 742</ref>.</note> and again urged against
                        sending of Japanese troops into neutral areas. The Foreign Office stated
                        that according to a report received from Shanghai the project to march
                        Japanese forces into such areas has been “abandoned” and “the question does
                        not arise”.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
